snippet.textDisplay: Great interview and I agree with much of what Mr Gates says, but isn't it a little bit silly to talk about range anxiety relating to EVs when the only electric car you've ever owned is like the least efficient one being sold? There are many EV options that cost a fraction of the price of a Taycan and offer better range, so it seems a little arbitrary/nitpicky to buy what is considered a premium car (an EV) from an overwhelmingly premium(ly priced) company (Porsche) and then deem questionable range as an issue that is still going to be a problem for most drivers. Like, Gates paid a double premium for style and then spent practically 10% of the interview equating that to "ah my toy isn't very efficient, EVs still have a long way to go" lol. Still a good interview though :D

snippet.textDisplay:
Maybe one of the best ways of convincing people about prevention & mitigation of runaway climate change premium costs are worth it, is to try to show them that when you take into account the often neglected (or should I say forgotten) costs of environmental cleanup, negative health impacts & the resulting losses to productivity & GDP; these are much greater overall than taking the sensible yet sometimes more difficult route. Indeed job losses & loss of life can be & are starting to be felt (Californian & Australian bushfires) as a result of not meeting the challenges much sooner; a state of affairs only set to worsen.

Politicians often cite protection of the economy [or not at the expense of] before climate change prevention but nobody seems YET to be asking them about economic losses from C.C. exacerbated natural disasters. The two examples stated above are prime ones.

Internationally, people are starting to be priced out of affordable insurance premiums, if indeed the industry's willing to provide such products that cover natural disasters; in some markets these are already being withdrawn due to climate change. Insurance industry has been preparing for this for at least the last 5 years or more. The knock-on effect for all of us who buy any kind of insurance will mean higher premiums as companies look to spread their costs.
